SECTION A: VARIABLES (10 Questions)
Basic Questions (1-5)
Q1. Create three variables: name (your name), age (your age), and city (your city). Print all three with labels.
Q2. What's wrong with these variable names? Explain why.
student = "John"
my-name = "Alice"
class = "Python"
student name = "Bob"

Q3. Create variables a = 10, b = 20, c = 30. Swap the values so that a becomes 20, b becomes 30, and c becomes 10. Print the results.
Q4. Assign the same value 100 to three variables x, y, and z in a single line. Then change only y to 200. Print all three.
Q5. Create a variable temp = 25. Now change it to "Twenty Five" (string). What happened to the variable type? Use type() to verify.
Scenario-Based Questions (6-10)
Q6. You're creating a student database. Create variables for: student ID, name, branch, year of study, and CGPA. Print a formatted student card.
Q7. Create variables for a product: product_name, original_price, discount_percent. Calculate and store the final_price. Print all details.
Q8. A user profile needs: username, email, phone number, and account creation year. Create these variables and print them in a nice format using f-strings.
Q9. You're tracking a game player: player_name, level, health, coins. Print their game status. Then the player collects 50 more coins - update and print again.
Q10. Create variables for a book: title, author, publication year, price, and availability (True/False). Print a book information card.

SECTION B: DATA TYPES (15 Questions)
Integer & Float Questions (11-15)
Q11. Calculate the area of a rectangle with length = 15.5 and width = 10.2. Print the result with 2 decimal places.
Q12. A student scored 456 marks out of 600. Calculate the percentage. Is it an integer or float? Why?
Q13. You have Rs. 1000. You buy 3 items costing Rs. 199.99 each. Calculate remaining money. What data type is the result?
Q14. Convert these to appropriate data types:

"123" to integer
45 to float
78.9 to integer
"3.14159" to float

Q15. Find what happens when you:
print(5 / 2)
print(5 // 2)
print(5.0 // 2)
Explain the difference.
String Questions (16-22)

Q16. Create a variable full_name = "Raj Kumar Sharma". Extract and print:

First name
Last name
Initials (R.K.S.)
Length of full name

Q17. Take a sentence: text = "python programming is fun". Convert it to:

All uppercase
All lowercase
Title case
Capitalized

Q18. Create two strings: first = "Hello" and second = "World". Combine them with a space in between. Then repeat the combined string 3 times.
Q19. Given email = "student@example.com", extract:

The username (before @)
The domain (after @)
Hint: Use string indexing and find() method

Q20. Create a string password = "Pass123". Check:

Length of password (is it >= 8?)
Does it contain "123"?
Convert to lowercase and check again

Q21. Given sentence = "I love Python programming", print:

5th character
Last 3 characters
Characters from index 2 to 7
Entire string in reverse (use slicing with step -1)

Q22. Create a message template: "Hello {name}, you have {count} new messages." Fill it with name="Alice" and count=5 using f-strings.
Boolean Questions (23-25)
Q23. Create boolean variables:

is_weekend = True
is_raining = False
has_umbrella = True

Determine: Should you go for a picnic? (weekend AND not raining)
Q24. A student needs 75% to pass and 90% for distinction. Given marks=85, create boolean variables passed and distinction. Print both.
Q25. Check and print True/False for:
pythonbool(0)
bool(1)
bool("")
bool(" ")
bool("False")
bool(None)
```
Explain the pattern you observe.

